# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: geological-society-of-america
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:geological-society-of-america/501-c-3-organization] A **501(c)(3) organization** is a United States corporation, trust, unincorporated association, or other type of organization exempt from federal income tax under section 501(c)(3) of Title 26 of the United States Code.
[src:geological-society-of-america/501-c-3-organization] It is one of the 29 types of 501(c) nonprofit organizations in the U.S.
[src:geological-society-of-america/501-c-3-organization] The 501(c)(3) exemption applies also for any non-incorporated community chest, fund, cooperating association or foundation organized and operated exclusively for those purposes.
[src:geological-society-of-america/501-c-3-organization] There are also supporting organizations—often referred to in shorthand form as *Friends of* organizations.
[src:geological-society-of-america/501-c-3-organization] 26 U.S.C. § 170 provides a deduction for federal income tax purposes, for some donors who make charitable contributions to most types of 501(c)(3) organizations, among others.
[src:geological-society-of-america/501-c-3-organization] Regulations specify which such deductions must be verifiable to be allowed (e.g., receipts for donations of $250 or more).
[src:geological-society-of-america/501-c-3-organization] The basic requirement of obtaining tax-exempt status is that the organization is specifically limited in powers to purposes that the IRS classifies as tax-exempt purposes.
[src:geological-society-of-america/501-c-3-organization] This limiting of the powers is crucial to obtaining tax exempt status with the IRS and then on the state level.
[src:geological-society-of-america/501-c-3-organization] Organizations acquire 501(c)(3) tax exemption by filing IRS Form 1023.
[src:geological-society-of-america/501-c-3-organization] As of 2006, the form must be accompanied by an $850 filing fee if the yearly gross receipts for the organization are expected to average $10,000 or more.
[src:geological-society-of-america/501-c-3-organization] If yearly gross receipts are expected to average less than $10,000, the filing fee is reduced to $400.
[src:geological-society-of-america/501-c-3-organization] The IRS released a software tool called Cyber Assistant in 2013, which was succeeded by Form 1023-EZ in 2014.
[src:geological-society-of-america/501-c-3-organization] There is an alternative way for an organization to obtain status if an organization has applied for a determination and either there is an actual controversy regarding a determination or the Internal Revenue Service has failed to make a determination.
[src:geological-society-of-america/501-c-3-organization] Prior to December 30, 1969, nonprofit organizations could declare themselves to be tax-exempt under Section 501(c)(3) without first obtaining Internal Revenue Service recognition by filing Form 1023 and receiving a determination letter.
[src:geological-society-of-america/501-c-3-organization] A nonprofit organization that did so prior to that date could still be subject to challenge of its status by the Internal Revenue Service.
[src:geological-society-of-america/501-c-3-organization] An individual may not take a tax deduction on gifts made to a 501(c)(3) organization that is organized and operated exclusively for the testing for public safety.
[src:geological-society-of-america/501-c-3-organization] In the case of tuition fees paid to a private 501(c)(3) school or a church school, the payments are not tax-deductible charitable contributions because they are payments for services rendered to the payee or the payee's children.
[src:geological-society-of-america/501-c-3-organization] The payments are not tax-deductible charitable contributions even if a significant portion of a church school's curriculum is religious education.
[src:geological-society-of-america/501-c-3-organization] For a payment to be a tax-deductible charitable contribution, it must be a voluntary transfer of money or other property with no expectation of procuring financial benefit equal to the transfer amount.
[src:geological-society-of-america/501-c-3-organization] Before donating to a 501(c)(3) organization, a donor can consult the searchable online IRS list of charitable organizations to verify that the organization qualifies to receive tax-deductible charitable contributions.
[src:geological-society-of-america/501-c-3-organization] Consumers may file IRS Form 13909, with documentation, to complain about inappropriate or fraudulent (i.e., fundraising, political campaigning, lobbying) activities by any 501(c)(3) organization.
[src:geological-society-of-america/501-c-3-organization] Most 501(c)(3) must disclose the names and addresses of certain large donors to the Internal Revenue Service on their annual returns, but this information is not required to be made available to the public, unless the organization is an independent foundation.
[src:geological-society-of-america/501-c-3-organization] Churches are generally exempt from this reporting requirement.
[src:geological-society-of-america/501-c-3-organization] Every 501(c)(3) organization must make available for public inspection its application for tax-exemption, including its Form 1023 or Form 1023-EZ and any attachments, supporting documents, and follow-up correspondence with the Internal Revenue Service.
[src:geological-society-of-america/501-c-3-organization] Annual returns must be publicly available for a three-year period beginning with the due date of the return, including any extension of time for filing.
[src:geological-society-of-america/501-c-3-organization] The Internal Revenue Service provides information about specific 501(c)(3) organizations through its Tax Exempt Organization Search online.
[src:geological-society-of-america/501-c-3-organization] A private nonprofit organization, GuideStar, provides information on 501(c)(3) organizations.
[src:geological-society-of-america/501-c-3-organization] ProPublica's Nonprofit Explorer provides copies of each organization's Form 990 and, for some organizations, audited financial statements.
[src:geological-society-of-america/501-c-3-organization] WikiCharities, is a nonprofit database of nonprofits and charities by name, location, and topic, that allows each organization to report its financials, leadership, contacts, and other activities.
[src:geological-society-of-america/501-c-3-organization] However, Open990 was a searchable database of information about organizations that had to shut down due to IRS delays in posting information online.
[src:geological-society-of-america/501-c-3-organization] Section 501(c)(3) organizations are prohibited from supporting political candidates, as a result of the Johnson Amendment enacted in 1954.
[src:geological-society-of-america/501-c-3-organization] Section 501(c)(3) organizations are subject to limits on lobbying, having a choice between two sets of rules establishing an upper bound for their lobbying activities.
[src:geological-society-of-america/501-c-3-organization] Section 501(c)(3) organizations risk loss of their tax-exempt status if these rules are violated.
[src:geological-society-of-america/501-c-3-organization] An organization that loses its 501(c)(3) status due to being engaged in political activities cannot subsequently qualify for 501(c)(3) status.
[src:geological-society-of-america/501-c-3-organization] As a result, it is common for 501(c)(3) organizations to have affiliated nonprofits that are classified as 501(c)(4) organizations, allowing the affiliate to engage in political activity without threatening 501(c)(3) status.
[src:geological-society-of-america/501-c-3-organization] Churches must meet specific requirements to obtain and maintain tax-exempt status; these are outlined in "IRS Publication 1828: Tax Guide for Churches and Religious Organizations".
[src:geological-society-of-america/501-c-3-organization] This guide outlines activities allowed and not allowed by churches under the 501(c)(3) designation.
[src:geological-society-of-america/501-c-3-organization] Schools for the preparation of its ministers.
[src:geological-society-of-america/501-c-3-organization] Having an established congregation served by an organized ministry is of central importance.
[src:geological-society-of-america/501-c-3-organization] Points 4, 6, 8, 11, 12, and 13 are also especially important.
[src:geological-society-of-america/501-c-3-organization] Nevertheless, the 14-point list is a guideline; it is not intended to be all-encompassing, and other facts and circumstances may be relevant factors.
[src:geological-society-of-america/501-c-3-organization] Although there is no definitive definition of a church for Internal Revenue Code purposes, in 1986 the United States Tax Court said that "A church is a coherent group of individuals and families that join together to accomplish the religious purposes of mutually held beliefs.
[src:geological-society-of-america/501-c-3-organization] The United States Tax Court has stated that, while a church can certainly broadcast its religious services by radio, radio broadcasts themselves do not constitute a congregation unless there is a group of people physically attending those religious services.
[src:geological-society-of-america/501-c-3-organization] A church can conduct worship services in various specific locations rather than in one official location.
[src:geological-society-of-america/501-c-3-organization] A church may have a significant number of people associate themselves with the church on a regular basis, even if the church does not have a traditional established list of individual members.
[src:geological-society-of-america/501-c-3-organization] In order to qualify as a tax-exempt church, church activities must be a significant part of the organization's operations.
[src:geological-society-of-america/501-c-3-organization] An organization whose operations include a substantial nonexempt commercial purposes, such as operating restaurants and grocery stores in a manner consistent with a particular religion's religious beliefs does not qualify as a tax-exempt church.
[src:geological-society-of-america/501-c-3-organization] In practice, hospital policies often don't cover outside contracted physicians or narrowly defined medically necessary services, leaving patients who technically qualify for charity care still responsible for significant medical bills.
[src:geological-society-of-america/501-c-3-organization] Organizations described in section 501(c)(3) are prohibited from conducting political campaign activities to intervene in elections to public office.
[src:geological-society-of-america/501-c-3-organization] Since section 501(c)(3)'s political-activity prohibition was enacted, "commentators and litigants have challenged the provision on numerous constitutional grounds", such as freedom of speech, vagueness, and equal protection and selective prosecution.
[src:geological-society-of-america/501-c-3-organization] Historically, Supreme Court decisions, such as *Regan v.
[src:geological-society-of-america/501-c-3-organization] Taxation with Representation of Washington*, suggested that the Court, if it were to squarely examine the political-activity prohibition of § 501(c)(3), would uphold it against a constitutional challenge.
[src:geological-society-of-america/501-c-3-organization] However, some have suggested that a successful challenge to the political activities prohibition of Section 501(c)(3) might be more plausible in light of *Citizens United v.
[src:geological-society-of-america/501-c-3-organization] In contrast to the prohibition on political campaign interventions by all section 501(c)(3) organizations, public charities (but not private foundations) may conduct a limited amount of lobbying to influence legislation.
[src:geological-society-of-america/501-c-3-organization] Although the law states that "no substantial part" of a public charity's activities can go to lobbying, charities with large budgets may lawfully expend a million dollars (under the "expenditure" test) or more (under the "substantial part" test) per year on lobbying.
[src:geological-society-of-america/501-c-3-organization] The Internal Revenue Service has never defined the term "substantial part" with respect to lobbying.
[src:geological-society-of-america/501-c-3-organization] To establish a safe harbor for the "substantial part" test, the United States Congress enacted §501(h), called the Conable election after its author, Representative Barber Conable.
[src:geological-society-of-america/501-c-3-organization] The section establishes limits based on operating budget that a charity can use to determine if it meets the substantial test.
[src:geological-society-of-america/501-c-3-organization] This changes the prohibition against direct intervention in partisan contests only for lobbying.
[src:geological-society-of-america/501-c-3-organization] The organization is now presumed in compliance with the substantiality test if they work within the limits.
[src:geological-society-of-america/501-c-3-organization] The Conable election requires a charity to file a declaration with the IRS and file a functional distribution of funds spreadsheet with their Form 990.
[src:geological-society-of-america/501-c-3-organization] IRS form 5768 is required to make the Conable election.
[src:geological-society-of-america/501-c-3-organization] A 501(c)(3) organization is allowed to conduct some or all of its charitable activities outside the United States.
[src:geological-society-of-america/501-c-3-organization] A 501(c)(3) organization is allowed to award grants to foreign charitable organizations if the grants are intended for charitable purposes and the grant funds are subject to the 501(c)(3) organization's control.
[src:geological-society-of-america/501-c-3-organization] Additional procedures are required of 501(c)(3) organizations that are private foundations.
[src:geological-society-of-america/501-c-3-organization] Donors' contributions to a 501(c)(3) organization are tax-deductible only if the contribution is for the use of the 501(c)(3) organization, and that the 501(c)(3) organization is not merely serving as an agent or conduit of a foreign charitable organization.
[src:geological-society-of-america/501-c-3-organization] The 501(c)(3) organization's management should review the grant application from the foreign organization, decide whether to award the grant based on the intended use of the funds, and require continuous oversight based on the use of funds.
[src:geological-society-of-america/501-c-3-organization] If the donor imposes a restriction or earmark that the contribution must be used for foreign activities, then the contribution is deemed to be for the foreign organization rather than the 501(c)(3) organization, and the contribution is not tax-deductible.
[src:geological-society-of-america/501-c-3-organization] The purpose of the grant to the foreign organization cannot include endorsing or opposing political candidates for elected office in any country.
[src:geological-society-of-america/501-c-3-organization] If a 501(c)(3) organization sets up and controls a foreign subsidiary to facilitate charitable work in a foreign country, then donors' contributions to the 501(c)(3) organization are tax-deductible even if intended to fund the foreign charitable activities.
[src:geological-society-of-america/adolph-knopf] Knopf was a member of the National Academy of Sciences and the American Academy of Arts and Sciences.
[src:geological-society-of-america/adolph-knopf] He served as president of the Geological Society of America in 1944 and received its Penrose Medal in 1959.
[src:geological-society-of-america/adolph-knopf] His second wife, Eleanora Knopf, was a notable geologist and frequent collaborator.
[src:geological-society-of-america/adolph-knopf] Knopf was born December 2, 1882, in San Francisco, California, to German American immigrants.
[src:geological-society-of-america/adolph-knopf] He grew up with his family on a ranch near Woodside, California.
[src:geological-society-of-america/adolph-knopf] Knopf entered the University of California, Berkeley, where he became a student of petrology under Andrew Lawson.
[src:geological-society-of-america/adolph-knopf] He earned a Bachelor of Science degree in mining geology in 1904 and a Master of Science degree in 1905.
[src:geological-society-of-america/adolph-knopf] That same year he spent the first of six summers surveying the mineral deposits of Alaska for the United States Geological Survey (USGS).
[src:geological-society-of-america/adolph-knopf] In 1906 he moved to Washington, D.C., to work for the USGS full-time.
[src:geological-society-of-america/adolph-knopf] The Alaskan Division, of which Knopf was one of about a dozen members, was considered the best geologic group in the USGS at that time.
[src:geological-society-of-america/adolph-knopf] Knopf's work on tin deposits in the Seward Peninsula became the basis of the dissertation for his Ph.D., which he received from Berkeley in 1909.
[src:geological-society-of-america/adolph-knopf] In Alaska he also discovered the minerals hulsite and paigeite.
[src:geological-society-of-america/adolph-knopf] In 1911 Knopf was promoted from assistant geologist to geologist.
[src:geological-society-of-america/adolph-knopf] Over the next nine years he undertook a series of field projects for the USGS, beginning with the mining district in Montana that includes the Boulder Batholith and continuing to other western states including Nevada and California.
[src:geological-society-of-america/adolph-knopf] In the latter state he surveyed the Gold Country.
[src:geological-society-of-america/adolph-knopf] After discovering that universities on the eastern seaboard were paying about double the USGS salaries, Knopf left the USGS for a teaching position, and a number of his colleagues followed suit.
[src:geological-society-of-america/adolph-knopf] Knopf began at Yale University in January 1920.
[src:geological-society-of-america/adolph-knopf] He encouraged students to work with the USGS as he had done; this helped mitigate the agency's brain drain following the departures.
[src:geological-society-of-america/adolph-knopf] Knopf began at Yale as an associate professor but was promoted to full professor in 1923.
[src:geological-society-of-america/adolph-knopf] He was named the Silliman Professor of Geology in 1937 and a Sterling Professor in 1938.
[src:geological-society-of-america/adolph-knopf] He was director of graduate studies from 1933 until his retirement from Yale in 1951.
[src:geological-society-of-america/adolph-knopf] Upon retiring he returned to his native Woodside, California, settling not far from his family's old ranch.
[src:geological-society-of-america/adolph-knopf] There he accepted a visiting appointment at the Stanford University School of Earth Sciences, where he remained until his death in 1966.
[src:geological-society-of-america/adolph-knopf] Knopf's field work continued through his Yale and Stanford appointments, again with a focus on western states.
[src:geological-society-of-america/adolph-knopf] He continued his work in the Boulder Batholith and investigated intrusive igneous rock bodies in the Spanish Peaks in Colorado.
[src:geological-society-of-america/adolph-knopf] He also contributed to the emerging field of geochronology, putting lower bounds of 2 billion years and later 4.5 billion years on the age of the Earth.
[src:geological-society-of-america/adolph-knopf] Knopf was elected to the National Academy of Sciences in 1931.
[src:geological-society-of-america/adolph-knopf] He was also a Fellow of the American Academy of Arts and Sciences and of the Geological Society of America.
[src:geological-society-of-america/adolph-knopf] He was president of the Geological Society of America in 1944, and he received the Penrose Medal in 1959.
[src:geological-society-of-america/adolph-knopf] In 1937 he was vice president of the Society of Economic Geologists.
[src:geological-society-of-america/adolph-knopf] In 1908 Knopf married Agnes Burchard Dillon.
[src:geological-society-of-america/adolph-knopf] They had three daughters and one son, though one of the daughters died in infancy.
[src:geological-society-of-america/adolph-knopf] Agnes died in 1918 in that year's flu pandemic.
[src:geological-society-of-america/adolph-knopf] In June 1920, Knopf married fellow USGS geologist Eleanora Frances Bliss, who as Eleanora Knopf became a frequent collaborator and travel companion.
[src:geological-society-of-america/adolph-knopf] When Adolph moved to Yale, which did not then hire women, Eleanora worked out of Adolph's office, teaching private classes and still accepting USGS assignments.
[src:geological-society-of-america/adolph-knopf] When they moved to California, Stanford hired her as a research associate.
[src:geological-society-of-america/adolph-knopf] Knopf died November 23, 1966, in Palo Alto, California.
[src:geological-society-of-america/adolph-knopf] In his will he endowed a chaired professorship at Yale.
[src:geological-society-of-america/adolph-knopf] The sitting Adolph Knopf Professor of Petrology is Shun-ichiro Karato.
[src:geological-society-of-america/adolph-knopf] Adolph and Eleanora Knopf also endowed a graduate fellowship in petrology at Stanford.
[src:geological-society-of-america/adolph-knopf] Mount Adolph Knopf in Juneau Borough, Alaska is named after him.
[src:geological-society-of-america/albert-w-bally] Bally started his career at Shell Oil Company, retiring as Chief Geologist after 27 years in 1981.
[src:geological-society-of-america/albert-w-bally] After retirement, he joined Rice University as chair of the Department of Geology and Geophysics.
[src:geological-society-of-america/albert-w-bally] He remained active in the department until his death in 2019.
[src:geological-society-of-america/albert-w-bally] In 1988, Bally was elected President of the Geological Society of America.
[src:geological-society-of-america/alexander-winchell] Winchell graduated from the Wesleyan University of Middletown, Connecticut, in 1847.
[src:geological-society-of-america/alexander-winchell] He then taught at Pennington Male Seminary of New Jersey, Amenia Seminary of New York (where he had previously been a student), an academy in Newbern, Alabama, and the Mesopotamia Female Seminary of Eutaw, the last of which was founded by him.
[src:geological-society-of-america/alexander-winchell] He became president of the Masonic University at Selma, Alabama, in 1853.
[src:geological-society-of-america/alexander-winchell] He was elected as a member of the American Philosophical Society in 1865.
[src:geological-society-of-america/alexander-winchell] In 1854 Winchell entered the service of the University of Michigan as professor of physics and civil engineering.
[src:geological-society-of-america/alexander-winchell] Eventually he became professor of geology and paleontology at Michigan.
[src:geological-society-of-america/alexander-winchell] In 1859, Winchell was appointed as State Geologist of Michigan for the newly formed second geological survey of the state.
[src:geological-society-of-america/alexander-winchell] He held the post until 1863 when the state did not appropriate funding to continue the survey.
[src:geological-society-of-america/alexander-winchell] The survey was resumed in 1869, and Winchell was reappointed in April.
[src:geological-society-of-america/alexander-winchell] Owing to conflicting opinions between Winchell and his superiors, he resigned in 1871.
[src:geological-society-of-america/alexander-winchell] In 1863 Winchell took up a lease on a cotton plantation near Vicksburg, Mississippi, under a plan devised by Gen.
[src:geological-society-of-america/alexander-winchell] Lorenzo Thomas to lease plantations along the Mississippi River to loyal men from the North, who would hire black laborers on terms prescribed by the army.
[src:geological-society-of-america/alexander-winchell] Winchell organized the Ann Arbor Cotton Company and sold stock to the university's president, whereupon he received a leave of absence to engage in cotton planting.
[src:geological-society-of-america/alexander-winchell] General Thomas set wages at a low level ($7 per month for men, $5 for women, minus the cost of medical attention and clothing).
[src:geological-society-of-america/alexander-winchell] Even then, many lessees defrauded the freedmen of their earnings.
[src:geological-society-of-america/alexander-winchell] In the winter of 1863–64, the Treasury Department briefly assumed control of the Mississippi Valley labor system, mandated a substantial increase in black wages, and contemplated leasing the plantations directly to the freedmen.
[src:geological-society-of-america/alexander-winchell] The venture brought him only problems, and after he returned to Michigan in 1864, his brother Martin, who was managing the plantation, was killed by guerrillas.
[src:geological-society-of-america/alexander-winchell] In 1872, he was appointed chancellor of Syracuse University.
[src:geological-society-of-america/alexander-winchell] The depression of 1873 affected both his personal finances and those of Syracuse, and these troubles led him to resign this position in 1874.
[src:geological-society-of-america/alexander-winchell] In 1875, he worked as a professor of geology and zoology at Vanderbilt University.
[src:geological-society-of-america/alexander-winchell] There, his views on evolution, as expressed in his book *Adamites and Preadamites: or, A Popular Discussion* (1878), were not acceptable to the University administration because they diverged from Biblical teaching.
[src:geological-society-of-america/alexander-winchell] Today the views on the "inferiority of the Negro" (quote from his 1878 book) would probably have been the focus of controversy.
[src:geological-society-of-america/alexander-winchell] In any case, he was obligated to resign in 1878.
[src:geological-society-of-america/alexander-winchell] In 1888, he co-founded the Geological Society of America in Ithaca, New York along with John J.
[src:geological-society-of-america/alexander-winchell] He served as the 3rd president of GSA in 1891.
[src:geological-society-of-america/alexander-winchell] He then returned to the University of Michigan, where he was professor of geology and paleontology.
[src:geological-society-of-america/alexander-winchell] His work in geology was not so significant as his teaching and popular lectures and writing in this field.
[src:geological-society-of-america/alexander-winchell] He was much concerned with reconciling science and religion.
[src:geological-society-of-america/alexander-winchell] He was an advocate of theistic evolution.
[src:geological-society-of-america/alexander-winchell] The fish **Clear chub** *Hybopsis winchelli* (Girard, 1856) is named after him.
[src:geological-society-of-america/alexander-winchell] The University of Michigan named a wing of the West Quad dormitory after Winchell, and Ann Arbor honored him with Winchell Park, a neighborhood park on the city's east side.
[src:geological-society-of-america/alexander-winchell] Winchell's name was removed from the dormitory in 2018, and the park was renamed after former Ann Arbor Public Schools board president Harold J.
[src:geological-society-of-america/alexander-winchell] In removing Winchell's name, the university described his *Preadamites* as an "unambiguously racist" work.
[src:geological-society-of-america/alfred-church-lane] Lane was educated at Harvard University and received his A.B. degree in 1883.
[src:geological-society-of-america/alfred-church-lane] Between 1883 and 1885 he taught mathematics at Harvard, then studied at the University of Heidelberg until 1887 before returning to Harvard to earn his Ph.D. in 1888.
[src:geological-society-of-america/alfred-church-lane] The following year he joined the Michigan State Geologic Survey as a petrographer, and he remained in that post into 1892 while also serving as an instructor at the Michigan College of Mines.
[src:geological-society-of-america/alfred-church-lane] He became assistant state geologist for Michigan in 1892, and from 1899 to 1909 he was the state geologist.
[src:geological-society-of-america/alfred-church-lane] Finally, he joined Tufts College in 1892, becoming the Pearson professor of geology and mineralogy.
[src:geological-society-of-america/alfred-church-lane] He retired from the college in 1936 as professor emeritus.
[src:geological-society-of-america/alfred-church-lane] While at Tufts, he served as vice president of the AAAS Division of Geology in 1907.
[src:geological-society-of-america/alfred-church-lane] He received an honorary D.Sc. from Tufts in 1913.
[src:geological-society-of-america/alfred-church-lane] From 1922 and 1946 he was chairman for the Committee on the Measurement of Geologic Time for the National Research Council.
[src:geological-society-of-america/alfred-church-lane] He served as a member of the Board of Visitors at Harvard Observatory in 1924.
[src:geological-society-of-america/alfred-church-lane] Alfred Lane was appointed as consultant of science to the Library of Congress in 1929; the first person to hold that post.
[src:geological-society-of-america/alfred-church-lane] In 1931, he was president of the Geological Society of America.
[src:geological-society-of-america/alfred-church-lane] He was awarded the Ballou Medal by Tufts College in 1940 for "distinguished service to education and the nation".
[src:geological-society-of-america/alfred-church-lane] During his career, he authored 1,087 publications.
[src:geological-society-of-america/andrew-lawson] Lawson was born on July 25, 1861, in Anstruther, Scotland.
[src:geological-society-of-america/andrew-lawson] He moved to Hamilton, Ontario, Canada with his parents at age six.
[src:geological-society-of-america/andrew-lawson] In 1883, he received his B.A. degree in natural science from the University of Toronto.
[src:geological-society-of-america/andrew-lawson] He worked for the Geological Survey of Canada while pursuing his graduate degrees.
[src:geological-society-of-america/andrew-lawson] He received his M.A. from the University of Toronto in 1885, and his Ph.D. from Johns Hopkins University in 1888.
[src:geological-society-of-america/andrew-lawson] In 1890, he left the Geological Survey of Canada to work as a consulting geologist in Vancouver.
[src:geological-society-of-america/andrew-lawson] In October of the same year, he accepted a position as assistant professor of Mineralogy and Geology at the University of California in Berkeley.
[src:geological-society-of-america/andrew-lawson] He became a full professor in 1892, and a professor emeritus from 1928 to his death on June 16, 1952.
[src:geological-society-of-america/andrew-lawson] Lawson was elected to the American Academy of Arts and Sciences in 1915, the United States National Academy of Sciences in 1924, and the American Philosophical Society in 1925.
[src:geological-society-of-america/andrew-lawson] He was president of the Geological Society of America in 1926.
[src:geological-society-of-america/andrew-lawson] He was a consulting geologist for the construction of the Golden Gate Bridge in the 1930s.
[src:geological-society-of-america/andrew-lawson] His home in the La Loma Park area of the Berkeley Hills in Berkeley, California, called the "Andrew Cowper Lawson House" (1908), was especially designed for him by noted architect Bernard Maybeck to withstand earthquakes.
[src:geological-society-of-america/andrew-lawson] The house is an official city designated Berkeley Landmark.
[src:geological-society-of-america/andrew-lawson] The mineral Lawsonite is named for him, as is the Lawson Adit, originally a mining construction research tunnel on UC Berkeley's campus.
[src:geological-society-of-america/andrew-lawson] 13,165 feet) in Sequoia National Park was officially named after him in 1976.
[src:geological-society-of-america/andrew-lawson] 1,128 feet), located west of the Briones Hills in Contra Costa County, California, is named for him.
[src:geological-society-of-america/anthony-j-naldrett] Between 1951 and 1953, he was a pilot in the Royal Air Force.
[src:geological-society-of-america/anthony-j-naldrett] In 1957, he obtained a degree in geology from the University of Cambridge.
[src:geological-society-of-america/anthony-j-naldrett] Later that year he moved to Canada, where he worked in Sudbury as a geologist for Falconbridge Nickel Mines.
[src:geological-society-of-america/anthony-j-naldrett] In 1959 he moved to Kingston, Ontario to attend Queen's University.
[src:geological-society-of-america/anthony-j-naldrett] He received an MSc (1961) and a PhD degree (1964) for his research on nickel deposits.
[src:geological-society-of-america/anthony-j-naldrett] Naldrett took a position working in the Geophysical Laboratory of the Carnegie Institution of Washington.
[src:geological-society-of-america/anthony-j-naldrett] In 1967, he returned to Canada as an assistant professor at the University of Toronto.
[src:geological-society-of-america/anthony-j-naldrett] In 1972, he was appointed a full Professor, and University Professor in 1984.
[src:geological-society-of-america/anthony-j-naldrett] He worked there until his retirement in 1998.
[src:geological-society-of-america/anthony-j-naldrett] The university made him an Emeritus Professor.
[src:geological-society-of-america/anthony-j-naldrett] Naldrett authored or co-authored 254 refereed publications, plus wrote or edited eight books covering his research in geology, mineralogy and chemistry of magmatic sulfide deposits and related rocks.
[src:geological-society-of-america/anthony-j-naldrett] In addition to his research, he consulted for over 35 companies including Chevron Corporation, Falconbridge, Western Mining Corporation, BHP, Rio Tinto, Cominco-American, Voisey's Bay Nickel, and Kennecott.
[src:geological-society-of-america/geological-society-of-america] The **Geological Society of America** (**GSA**) is a nonprofit organization dedicated to the advancement of the geosciences.
[src:geological-society-of-america/geological-society-of-america] The society was founded in Ithaca, New York, in 1888 by Alexander Winchell, John J.
[src:geological-society-of-america/geological-society-of-america] Procter and Edward Orton and has been headquartered at 3300 Penrose Place, Boulder, Colorado, US, since 1967.
[src:geological-society-of-america/geological-society-of-america] GSA began with 100 members under its first president, James Hall.
[src:geological-society-of-america/geological-society-of-america] In 1889 Mary Emilie Holmes became its first female member.
[src:geological-society-of-america/geological-society-of-america] It grew slowly but steadily to 600 members until 1931, when a nearly $4 million endowment from 1930 president R.
[src:geological-society-of-america/geological-society-of-america] As of December 2017, GSA had more than 25,000 members in over 100 countries.
[src:geological-society-of-america/geological-society-of-america] The society has six regional sections in North America, three interdisciplinary interest groups, and eighteen specialty divisions.
[src:geological-society-of-america/geological-society-of-america] The stated mission of GSA is "to advance geoscience research and discovery, service to society, stewardship of Earth, and the geosciences profession".
[src:geological-society-of-america/geological-society-of-america] Its main activities are sponsoring scientific meetings and publishing scientific literature, particularly the peer-reviewed journals *Geological Society of America Bulletin*, published continuously since 1889, and *Geology*, published since 1973.
[src:geological-society-of-america/geological-society-of-america] In 2005, GSA introduced its online-only journal *Geosphere*, and in February 2009, GSA began publishing *Lithosphere* (both also peer-reviewed).
[src:geological-society-of-america/geological-society-of-america] *Geosphere* and *Lithosphere* are open access as of 2018.
[src:geological-society-of-america/geological-society-of-america] GSA's monthly news and science magazine, *GSA Today*, is also open access online.
[src:geological-society-of-america/geological-society-of-america] GSA also publishes three book series: *Special Papers*, *Memoirs*, and *Field Guides*.
[src:geological-society-of-america/geological-society-of-america] A third major activity is awarding research grants to graduate students.
[src:geological-society-of-america/geological-society-of-america] GSA issues Position Statements "in support of and consistent with the GSA's Vision and Mission to develop consensus on significant professional, technical, and societal issues of relevance to the geosciences community.
[src:geological-society-of-america/geological-society-of-america] The Geological Society of America (GSA) supports the scientific conclusions that Earth's climate is changing; the climate changes are due in part to human activities; and the probable consequences of the climate changes will be significant and blind to geopolitical boundaries.
[src:geological-society-of-america/geological-society-of-america] Furthermore, the potential implications of global climate change and the time scale over which such changes will likely occur require active, effective, long-term planning.
[src:geological-society-of-america/geological-society-of-america] While the precise magnitude and rate of climate change cannot be predicted with absolute certainty, significant change will affect the planet and stress its inhabitants.
